hook.real_world_problem:
This code silently crashes when the user isn't found:

```java
public String getEmailForUser(int userId) {
    User user = userRepository.findById(userId);  // might return null!
    return user.getEmail();  // NullPointerException if user is null
}
```

The traditional fix — null-check — is verbose and easy to forget:
```java
public String getEmailForUser(int userId) {
    User user = userRepository.findById(userId);
    if (user != null) {
        return user.getEmail();
    }
    return "unknown@example.com";
}
```

**With Optional:**
```java
public String getEmailForUser(int userId) {
    return userRepository.findById(userId)  // returns Optional<User>
        .map(User::getEmail)                // transform if present
        .orElse("unknown@example.com");     // default if empty
}
```

One line. No null check. No NPE possible. The method signature declares: 'this might not return a value.'

**Why Optional is better than null:**
1. The type system tells callers 'this might be absent' — they can't accidentally forget to check
2. Clean chaining API (map, filter, flatMap) instead of nested if-null checks
3. Integrates naturally with Streams — findFirst(), max(), min() all return Optional

Today you learn to write null-safe code the modern Java way.

concept_explanation.optional_creation:
**Creating an Optional:**

```java
import java.util.Optional;

// Contains a value
Optional<String> name = Optional.of("Aisha");     // non-null value

// Might be null — safe wrapper
Optional<String> maybe = Optional.ofNullable(getUserName());  // null → empty

// Definitely empty
Optional<String> empty = Optional.empty();
```

**The three factory methods:**
- `Optional.of(value)` — value MUST be non-null (throws NPE if null)
- `Optional.ofNullable(value)` — null → empty Optional, non-null → present Optional
- `Optional.empty()` — explicitly empty

**Common usage pattern:**
```java
// Instead of returning null:
public Optional<User> findUser(int id) {
    User user = database.lookup(id);
    return Optional.ofNullable(user);  // wraps result — null becomes empty
}
```

`Optional.ofNullable` is the go-to for wrapping values that might be null (Map.get, database results, etc.).

concept_explanation.orElse_orElseGet_orElseThrow:
**Extracting values — four ways:**

```java
Optional<String> name = Optional.ofNullable(getName());

// orElse: default value (always computed)
String result1 = name.orElse("Unknown");

// orElseGet: default computed lazily (Supplier — only called if empty)
String result2 = name.orElseGet(() -> computeDefault());  // more efficient

// orElseThrow: throw if empty
String result3 = name.orElseThrow(() -> new UserNotFoundException("Name not found"));

// get(): use ONLY after isPresent check — otherwise NoSuchElementException
if (name.isPresent()) {
    String r = name.get();  // only safe inside isPresent check
}
```

**orElse vs orElseGet:**
```java
// orElse always evaluates the argument — even if Optional is present:
String s = optional.orElse(expensiveComputation());  // expensiveComputation() ALWAYS runs

// orElseGet only evaluates when Optional is empty:
String s = optional.orElseGet(() -> expensiveComputation());  // only if empty
```

Rule of thumb: use `orElse` for simple constants. Use `orElseGet` for computed defaults (database calls, object creation).

concept_explanation.ifPresent_ifPresentOrElse:
**Acting on the value — ifPresent:**

```java
Optional<User> user = findUser(userId);

// ifPresent: run action only if present
user.ifPresent(u -> System.out.println("Welcome, " + u.getName()));

// ifPresent with method reference
user.ifPresent(emailService::sendWelcomeEmail);

// Java 9+: ifPresentOrElse — handle both cases
user.ifPresentOrElse(
    u -> System.out.println("Found: " + u.getName()),
    () -> System.out.println("User not found")
);
```

`ifPresent` replaces the pattern:
```java
if (user != null) {
    emailService.sendWelcomeEmail(user);
}
```

concept_explanation.optional_map:
**`map(Function<T, R>)`** — transform the value if present:

```java
Optional<User> user = findUser(userId);

// Get user's department — empty Optional if user not found
Optional<String> dept = user.map(User::getDepartment);

// Chain maps:
Optional<Integer> deptSize = user
    .map(User::getDepartment)
    .map(String::length);  // how long is the dept name?

// Practical: get email or default
String email = findUser(userId)
    .map(User::getEmail)
    .orElse("no-reply@example.com");
```

**map on empty Optional → empty Optional.** The function is only applied if the Optional has a value. This is what makes chaining safe — no null checks needed anywhere in the chain.

```java
// Without Optional — 3 null checks:
String email = null;
if (user != null) {
    String dept = user.getDepartment();
    if (dept != null) {
        email = dept.getPrimaryContact();
    }
}

// With Optional — 0 null checks:
String email = Optional.ofNullable(user)
    .map(User::getDepartment)
    .map(Department::getPrimaryContact)
    .orElse(null);
```

concept_explanation.optional_filter:
**`filter(Predicate<T>)`** — keep value only if it passes the test:

```java
Optional<User> activeUser = findUser(userId)
    .filter(u -> u.isActive());

// Chain filter and map:
String email = findUser(userId)
    .filter(User::isActive)      // empty if not active
    .map(User::getEmail)         // get email only if active
    .orElse("inactive@example.com");

// Filter by condition:
Optional<Product> affordableProduct = findProduct(productId)
    .filter(p -> p.getPrice() < 1000);
```

`filter` on an empty Optional → still empty. `filter` on present Optional → present if predicate true, empty if predicate false.

concept_explanation.optional_flatMap:
**`flatMap(Function<T, Optional<R>>)`** — for when map would return Optional<Optional<T>>:

```java
// Problem: map returns Optional<Optional<String>>
Optional<Optional<String>> nested = user.map(u -> u.getEmail());  // if getEmail() returns Optional<String>

// flatMap unwraps one level:
Optional<String> email = user.flatMap(u -> u.getEmail());

// Practical chaining — user → order → tracking
Optional<String> trackingInfo = findUser(userId)
    .flatMap(User::getLastOrder)          // returns Optional<Order>
    .flatMap(Order::getTrackingInfo);     // returns Optional<String>
```

**When to use flatMap**: when the function you're applying ITSELF returns an Optional. `map` for `T → R`. `flatMap` for `T → Optional<R>`.

concept_explanation.optional_from_streams:
**Optional from Stream terminals** — you've already been using these:

```java
List<Product> catalog = ...;

// findFirst returns Optional
Optional<Product> first = catalog.stream()
    .filter(p -> p.getPrice() < 500)
    .findFirst();

// Handle it:
first.ifPresent(p -> System.out.println("Found: " + p.getName()));
Product p = first.orElseThrow(() -> new ProductNotFoundException("No affordable product"));

// min/max return Optional
Optional<Product> cheapest = catalog.stream()
    .min(Comparator.comparingDouble(Product::getPrice));

// Chain directly:
String cheapestName = catalog.stream()
    .min(Comparator.comparingDouble(Product::getPrice))
    .map(Product::getName)
    .orElse("No products");
```

This is why Optional was introduced in Java 8 — it was designed to be the return type of these stream terminal operations. `findFirst()`, `findAny()`, `min()`, `max()`, and `reduce()` (one-argument form) all return `Optional<T>`.

concept_explanation.optional_as_return_type:
**Designing APIs with Optional as return type:**

```java
// Good API design:
public Optional<User> findUserByEmail(String email) {
    return Optional.ofNullable(userMap.get(email));  // never returns null
}

public Optional<Product> getMostExpensive(List<Product> catalog) {
    return catalog.stream().max(Comparator.comparingDouble(Product::getPrice));
}

// Bad — don't use Optional as parameter type:
// public void setName(Optional<String> name) {}  // WRONG — use overloads instead
// public String getName(Optional<String> default) {}  // WRONG

// Bad — don't use Optional for fields or collections:
// private Optional<String> name;  // WRONG — use null check or object instead
// Map<String, Optional<Product>> map;  // WRONG — unnecessary wrapping
```

**Optional is designed for RETURN TYPES only.** It's a signal to callers: 'this method might not return a value, and you MUST handle that case.' Not for fields, not for parameters.

concept_explanation.anti_patterns:
**Optional anti-patterns to avoid:**

```java
// ANTI-PATTERN 1: Using get() without isPresent()
User user = findUser(id).get();  // NoSuchElementException if empty!
// Fix: use orElse, orElseGet, orElseThrow, or ifPresent

// ANTI-PATTERN 2: Optional for primitive types
Optional<Integer> count = Optional.of(42);  // boxed — use OptionalInt
OptionalInt count = OptionalInt.of(42);  // better

// ANTI-PATTERN 3: Checking isPresent then get — just use orElse
if (optional.isPresent()) {
    return optional.get();  // verbose — same as optional.orElseThrow()
}

// ANTI-PATTERN 4: Returning Optional.of(null) — throws NPE!
return Optional.of(maybeNull);  // WRONG if maybeNull could be null
return Optional.ofNullable(maybeNull);  // CORRECT

// ANTI-PATTERN 5: Using Optional as method parameter
public void process(Optional<String> input) {}  // WRONG design
public void process(String input) {}  // + overload for default
```

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
// 6 lines, hard to read, easy to forget a check:
public String getUserCity(String userId) {
    User user = users.get(userId);
    if (user != null) {
        Account account = user.getAccount();
        if (account != null) {
            Address address = account.getAddress();
            if (address != null) {
                return address.getCity();
            }
        }
    }
    return "Unknown City";
}
```

```java
public double getTopOrderValue(String userId) {
    return Optional.ofNullable(users.get(userId))
        .map(User::getOrders)             // get order list (might be null)
        .filter(orders -> !orders.isEmpty())
        .flatMap(orders -> orders.stream() // stream returns Optional<Order>
            .max(Comparator.comparingDouble(Order::getValue)))
        .map(Order::getValue)
        .orElse(0.0);
}
```

flatMap is needed here because `orders.stream().max(...)` returns `Optional<Order>` — if we used map, we'd get `Optional<Optional<Order>>`.

worked_example.final_code:
import java.util.*;

class Address { String city; Address(String c) { city=c; } String getCity() { return city; } }
class Account { Address address; Account(Address a) { address=a; } Address getAddress() { return address; } }
class Order   { double value; Order(double v) { value=v; } double getValue() { return value; } }

class User {
    String name;
    Account account;
    List<Order> orders;
    User(String n, Account a, List<Order> o) { name=n; account=a; orders=o; }
    Account getAccount() { return account; }
    List<Order> getOrders() { return orders; }
    public String toString() { return name; }
}

public class OptionalDemo {
    static Map<String, User> users = new HashMap<>();

    static String getUserCity(String userId) {
        return Optional.ofNullable(users.get(userId))
            .map(User::getAccount)
            .map(Account::getAddress)
            .map(Address::getCity)
            .orElse("Unknown City");
    }

    static double getTopOrderValue(String userId) {
        return Optional.ofNullable(users.get(userId))
            .map(User::getOrders)
            .filter(orders -> !orders.isEmpty())
            .flatMap(orders -> orders.stream()
                .max(Comparator.comparingDouble(Order::getValue)))
            .map(Order::getValue)
            .orElse(0.0);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        users.put("U001", new User("Aisha",
            new Account(new Address("Hyderabad")),
            Arrays.asList(new Order(5000), new Order(2200), new Order(8100))));
        users.put("U002", new User("Raj",
            new Account(null),  // no address
            Arrays.asList(new Order(1500))));

        System.out.println(getUserCity("U001"));    // Hyderabad
        System.out.println(getUserCity("U002"));    // Unknown City (address is null)
        System.out.println(getUserCity("U999"));    // Unknown City (user not found)
        System.out.println(getTopOrderValue("U001")); // 8100.0
        System.out.println(getTopOrderValue("U999")); // 0.0
    }
}

